The aarch64-paging crate lets you create page tables according to the AArch64 Virtual Memory System Architecture. use aarch64_paging::{ idmap::IdMap, paging::{Attributes, MemoryRegion},
}; const ASID: usize = 1;
const ROOT_LEVEL: usize = 1; // Create a new page table with identity mapping.
let mut idmap = IdMap::new(ASID, ROOT_LEVEL);
// Map a 2 MiB region of memory as read-only.
idmap.map_range( &MemoryRegion::new(0x80200000, 0x80400000), Attributes::NORMAL | Attributes::NON_GLOBAL | Attributes::READ_ONLY,
).unwrap();
// Set `TTBR0_EL1` to activate the page table.
idmap.activate(); For now it only supports EL1, but support for other exception levels should be straightforward to add. This is used in Android for the Protected VM Firmware . There's no easy way to run this example, as it needs to run on real hardware or under QEMU.

